I went into the album expecting it to sound lame as I had come to assume of Emmures work but Trash Folder as a song had me hooked.  You literally have to join in when he starts with "I make the wave, I set the stage."  It's so good.  They embraced nu metal really well.

I dunno as soon as Gypsy Disco dropped as the lead single I was like wow is this...real self reflection from Frankie?  Not to mention it's hard to not belt out along to the chorus and the stupid detuned breakdown to a GG Allin voice clip.

But I legit found myself loving every second of Hindsight as an album.  I mean let's be real it was probably because of Josh Travis.  But my god that album goes so hard, and surprisingly lacking in Frankie's usual tasteless approach (Sandy Hook phone call sample anyone?)

Gotta admit Emmure really turned it around as a band.  They used to be guys I was constantly making fun of (the breakdown of When Keeping it Real Goes Wrong was a long running joke between me and friends, along with "haha get it a Cheerios box is Emmure tablature")

This album is more a part of me than any piece of music ever could be.  It's been here for me in my roughest moments and happiest ones, and I hope this thread introduces it to new people and it does the same for them. It's such a beautiful work of art.
https://t.co/JzTCsJdyFA

Is it perfect?  Probably not.  But I don't care.
It is to me.
I can't think of anything that could really improve it more than it is.
As long as I perceive the world around me through my own eyes, and this life I lead is mine, this album will always be the best in it.

Enduring the 50 minute drive to college every day back in 2019, this album was my soundtrack there and back, 4 days a week, for months.  It was the first album I found myself having the confidence to really *sing* along to.  And a year later, even start screaming along  to.

Do yourself a favor, sit yourself down in bed late at night, turn off all your lights except your laptop/tablet/phone screen and burn through this whole album staring into the dark corners of your room.  It is an unforgettable experience.

All the same cries of "it's too different" from people expecting What It Is To Burn 2.0 and just wanting more same-y love songs about driving your girlfriend home, not expecting complex music about a sick childhood friend's sister dying and his house sinking into the ground.

Critics fucking hated it.  Finch fans fucking hated it.  Finch wouldn't release more music until 2009 with a 4 track EP that admittedly had some amazing material ("Chinese Organ Thieves" is my designated crying-on-command song) and after that, one final full-length LP in 2014.

Sure you can pick out very clear influences, Incubus and Faith No More being the most notable examples, but none of Finch's influences or even contemporaries (Glassjaw for example was focusing on post-9/11 America and our national vices) came close to something this cohesive.

AND CAN WE JUST TALK ABOUT THAT ALBUM ART THOUGH.  Jeff Soto knocked it out the park.  This album may not have been an opera but it feels like one thanks to the art tying together this singular theme of surreality and mental decline, all right in your home town. https://t.co/HHbmVJKwEK

This album is out of this fucking world.  From the chorus of "Brother Bleed Brother" and the bridge of "Fireflies" to the breakdown of "A Piece of Mind" (my favorite song on the album) and the opening of "Bitemarks and Bloodstains" it is just so amazing.
https://t.co/b0dUVZtayj

It was like trying to run through a field on a cold gloomy day, movement sluggish and thoughts erratic, and realizing you weren't conscious but either comatose or lucid dreaming or both.  It was incomparable and even now that opening still gives me chills.

Then, at 2 am by the light of my TV and my laptop burning a hole in my blanket on a hot summer night, I decided to approach their second album, knowing I already liked one song off it.  And so, coming from pop punk and love songs, I was met with this.
https://t.co/BJxDVT3bN0

8th grade me, still running on early Deftones, ate that first Finch album up, songs like Awake were just pure bliss to me.  But the lyrics of early Finch felt corny at best a lot of the time, though maybe I was just salty about being single back then.
https://t.co/wWVgweuAB2

But I wouldn't return to Finch for at least 5 years.  It wasn't until, hear me out, a motherfucking My Little Pony video that I found my way back.  Ponies - The Anthology had a few seconds of What It Is To Burn in it, and from there I dove right back in.
https://t.co/EZdNoSEORL

Easily my favorite off that soundtrack even competing with acts like Yellowcard, Goldfinger, The Academy Is... and - Comeback Kid?  Oh fuck I just realized one of my favorite melodic hardcore acts was on that OST too, though I didn't vibe with it then.
https://t.co/NOG9BV5olv

That strange rhythm, that riff that feels like it's mocking you at your lowest point, that amazing chorus as the whispers through gritted teeth turn to threatening roars, the soaring chords of the bridge, and the gasp as the song ends as abruptly as it started.  Unbelievable.

I didn't really have a main point in mind for all this, it's just a fun trip down memory lane.  I've been listening to Pop Punk for 10 years now and kinda going back to where it all began is a major "Wow" moment.  It's just so nostalgic.  A zoomer thing to say I know, but still.

But then Life's Not Out to Get You came out and I knew we all had something special on our hands and these kids knew what was up.  By that point I expanded more to Knuckle Puck, Wonder Years, Trash Boat, and more emo-ish acts like Somos and Modern Baseball.

Like god remember when Neck Deep just had two EPs out on Youtube, Ben's voice was so much more gruff and angry, their sound so much more rocky and kinda cacophonous.  Then Wishful Thinking came out and I actually remember being disappointed by its more clean approach...

I swear to you 90% of what I listen to in this vein was all recommendations from either a Youtube comment under a TSSF video, or the booklet of Under Soil and Dirt thanking all these bands for support and influence.  That and the "Defend Pop Punk" Podcast too.

I needed MORE.  I expanded into every nook and cranny of the scene.  From the sillier melodrama of Handguns, and Such Gold's harsher fusion of pop and classic post-hardcore, to Title Fight's grungey meltdowns, This Time Next Year's pop punk purism, and Transit's Boston Emo sound.

That whole album was sonic crack for me, for MONTHS AND MONTHS.  From the its soaring shouting highs and blunt self diagnoses of "I can never be calm again" to its acoustic lows warning of "This body's closed until further notice."  A true classic now and forever.

That chorus.  That duet of "Never gonna be the same again, bury me I'm not your friend.  You have your sword I have my pen, measuring might is a means to an end" and that FUCKING SLAMMING ENDING with "Not broke, just bent." It blew me away.

Holy. SHIT.  That intro riff just GOT ME.  That chugging not-quite-pop but not so hardcore, this riff that like I said before just feels like you're constantly at war with something and can't quite actualize it in a healthy way.  It was unlike anything I'd heard in my 15 years.

But still for a good few years ADTR was kinda my only link to it.  Then I logged into youtube one gloomy spring afternoon and saw a suggestion for "Swords & Pens" by TSSF.  "Heh, kinda like Black Veil Brides" I chuckled to my edgy self and clicked on it...
https://t.co/EckbRPXGCv

From there I explored post-hardcore further, beyond just listening to Say Hello to Sunshine by Finch on repeat, I got into bands like The Used, Escape the Fate (post-Ronnie), Saosin, Story of the Year and others.  Fantastic sounds.  Still stick with them today.

Like it got me into metalcore (an Austrian Death Machine song from the same video helped, along with an As I Lay Dying song I grew up with), and then I started seeking that same heavier pop punk sound.  Less like Blink and Green Day, more like hardcore with pop chord progressions

A Day to Remember was my gateway I think, for pop punk and metalcore.  Never thought they could be combined.  Then lo and behold, I was watching a Garrys Mod video and at the end I got hit with "I'm Made of Wax, Larry, What Are You Made Of?" and I got fucking HOOKED on that sound

Man it's been almost a decade since I got properly into Pop Punk again.  I had a CD of American Idiot back in 7th grade and bumped it a lot, and even used to vibe to some Blink in 8th grade but it never really *got* me.
